Obstructive sleep apnea involves upper airway narrowing during sleep, particularly due to structural abnormalities affecting the jaw or temporomandibular joint region. Among the listed choices, bilateral TMJ ankylosis leads to significant restriction of mandibular movement, resulting in posterior displacement of the tongue and collapse of the airway—a known cause of obstructive sleep apnea. While the other options relate to nasal or orbital issues, none are directly tied to airway obstruction via mandibular mechanics.

